land reform decentralized governance and rural development in west bengal siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display land reform decentralized governance and rural development in west bengal type scid working paper 314 author s pranab bardhan dilip mookherjee published 02 1 07 region india download pdf abstract since the late 1970s the west bengal government has implemented comprehensive reforms of agrarian institutions including land reform land redistribution tenancy registration and democratic decentralization devolution of agricultural development program delivery to elected local governments we provide an overview of our research findings concerning the accountability of local governments and impact of their program interventions on farm yields and agricultural incomes programs administered by the local governments were reasonably well targeted to the poor with few exceptions targeting improved as local elections became more contested and deteriorated with greater socio economic inequality the tenancy registration program distribution of agricultural minikits irdp credit and irrigation programs administered by local governments had significant effects on subsequent growth in farm productivity and incomes the benefits diffused widely among farms within the village and trickled down to landless agricultural workers in the form of higher wage rates stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
